The Porsche 911 GT3 is a high-performance homologation model of the Porsche 911 sports car. It is a line of high-performance models, which began with the 1973 911 Carrera RS.

The GT3 has had a successful racing career in the one-make national and regional Porsche Carrera Cup and GT3 Cup Challenge series, as well as the international Porsche Supercup supporting the FIA F1 World Championship.

The engine of the 996 GTâs and Turbo set it apart from 996 Carrera models, as it shared nothing with the standard so-called âintegrated dry sumpâ (eg. wet-sump) flat-six engine used in the water-cooled 996 Carrera engine introduced in MY1999. The 996 GT engine is naturally aspirated and based on.

The Mezgerâ racing engine used in the 962 and 911 GT1 race cars. That engine was known as the âMezgerâ engine, after its designer Hans Mezger. The engine uses the original air-cooled 911âs versatile dry-sump crankcase, with an external oil reservoir. The 996 GT3 has 360 PS (265 kW; 355 hp), compared to the 300 PS (221 kW; 296 hp) of the standard 996.

In GT3 configuration, this so-called âsplitâ crankcase (meaning the parting line of crankcase is on the crankshaft centreline) uses, instead of a fan and finned cylinders, separate water jackets added onto each side of the crankcase to cool banks of three cylinders with water pumped through a radiator.

Tutorial: Echo Printing.

What do you want to challenge us with next?

Shoutout to @oppo and @eyecannndy for the inspiration.

Tutorial:
1. Before shooting, choose clothing that contrasts well with the background because you need to magic mask/auto mask/rotobrush.
2. Put your camera on a tripod and shoot yourself walking in a zig zag position towards the camera. Make sure each spot you walk to is closer to the camera than the previous spot.
3. In your editor, speed ramp or cut your clips so there is ~6 frames of you walking from spot to spot.
4. Magic mask yourself from the background. Your mask does NOT need to be perfect because when you blur, the edges disappear. Feather the mask edge with a blur and erode/contract so it isn't so pixelated. Export or precomp the mask with alpha and then reimport.
5. Layer your timeline with the sped up clip on bottom and echos above then cut the echo clips so they appear when you want them to. Once done cutting, freeze frame each echo.
6. Add directional blur to all your moving echos. The blur should be in the direction you are walking. Play around with blur strength - the same setting on a far and close echo will have dramatically different results.
7.Put your first masked clip on top of all the echos and you're golden.

Tips to make it look even better:
- freeze frame the shadows at your feet so your echos aren't floating in space - do this with a simple feathered polygon
- keyframe the strength of the blur to increase every time you walk past an echo (for example, walking from desk to table, we increased strength of blur on the echos from window to desk).
